1
00:00:00,400 --> 00:00:02,000
<i>Previously on</i> Jericho

2
00:00:02,300 --> 00:00:03,600
Some of them were on planes

3
00:00:03,700 --> 00:00:05,200
that landed in the middle of nowhere.

4
00:00:05,700 --> 00:00:07,000
They've been walking for weeks.

5
00:00:07,600 --> 00:00:09,100
They must have gone through hell.

6
00:00:09,500 --> 00:00:10,500
Oh, my God.

7
00:00:12,500 --> 00:00:14,400
At the current levels of consumption,

8
00:00:14,500 --> 00:00:17,799
we will be completely
out of gas and diesel in two weeks.

9
00:00:17,800 --> 00:00:19,799
There's a woman in that
group of refugees that

10
00:00:19,800 --> 00:00:22,000
Bill is processing.
I think you should talk to her.

11
00:00:22,600 --> 00:00:23,600
Hello, Rob.

12
00:00:23,800 --> 00:00:25,899
Someone on my team sold us all out.

13
00:00:25,900 --> 00:00:26,999
You're smart enough to know

14
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:29,400
that they would say anything
to get you to talk, Sarah.

15
00:00:30,600 --> 00:00:32,400
Get the package.

16
00:00:44,700 --> 00:00:46,100
We're the United States Marines,

17
00:00:46,400 --> 00:00:47,500
and we're here to help.

18
00:00:47,900 --> 00:00:49,499
... and those are to restore lights,

19
00:00:49,500 --> 00:00:52,900
power and infrastructure
to Kansas, one town at a time.

20
00:00:57,199 --> 00:00:59,399
Something's wrong about all this,
all right? Trust me.

21
00:00:59,400 --> 00:01:02,541
They've got somebody on the edge of town
pretending to be their headquarters.

22
00:01:02,800 --> 00:01:04,000
Is any of this real?

23
00:01:04,200 --> 00:01:06,399
- The gun's real.
- Hands up. Get them up!

24
00:01:06,400 --> 00:01:07,900
What the hell do we do with them?

25
00:01:08,100 --> 00:01:09,900
You will leave your weapons on the tank,

26
00:01:10,200 --> 00:01:11,400
and you will move out!

27
00:01:11,500 --> 00:01:13,100
- What do we do with that?
- Stanley,

28
00:01:13,500 --> 00:01:14,500
got room in your barn?

29
00:01:14,600 --> 00:01:16,400
- Seriously?
- Why not?

30
00:01:17,800 --> 00:01:19,400
Never know when you might need a tank.

31
00:01:47,600 --> 00:01:49,300
You're making too much noise.

32
00:01:49,400 --> 00:01:50,500
Sorry.

33
00:01:51,700 --> 00:01:52,700
Where did it go?

34
00:01:55,000 --> 00:01:56,000
There it is.

35
00:02:06,900 --> 00:02:08,900
- It's locked.
- We shouldn't go in.

36
00:02:12,900 --> 00:02:13,900
Go in here.

37
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:16,100
- Why do I have to?
- So we can eat.

38
00:02:26,100 --> 00:02:27,100
You see it?

39
00:02:28,400 --> 00:02:29,400
Katie?

40
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:41,500
<i>Come on, Jake,
there's a line here.

41
00:02:41,600 --> 00:02:42,900
<i>Did you hear about the tank?

42
00:02:43,100 --> 00:02:44,500
<i>Those Marines coming or what?

43
00:02:44,600 --> 00:02:47,400
<i>Everybody, just calm down!
You'll get your share.

44
00:02:49,400 --> 00:02:50,800
<i>You'll get your rations!

45
00:02:51,500 --> 00:02:53,300
<i>People, please, back up!

46
00:02:54,700 --> 00:02:56,000
How is Gray handling this?

47
00:02:56,066 --> 00:02:57,099
You better get in there.

48
00:02:57,100 --> 00:02:59,100
I think we really screwed
ourselves this time.

49
00:02:59,200 --> 00:03:02,499
You said everyone in the shelter gets
half-rations until the Marines come.

50
00:03:02,500 --> 00:03:05,000
Well, the Marines aren't coming,
and you've known all along.

51
00:03:05,200 --> 00:03:06,900
We did the best that we could.

52
00:03:06,973 --> 00:03:08,899
People had to believe
that help was on the way.

53
00:03:08,900 --> 00:03:09,999
And you know what?

54
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:13,100
Half-rations is a lot more than
those refugees had before they got here.

55
00:03:13,800 --> 00:03:14,900
Did you know about this?

56
00:03:15,100 --> 00:03:16,900
The Marines...
That they were con artists?

57
00:03:18,300 --> 00:03:20,600
Yeah, but we didn't give them
any of our supplies.

58
00:03:20,700 --> 00:03:23,600
And Gray is right. The last thing
this town needs is to lose hope.

59
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:26,100
Hope won't keep
my friends from starving.

60
00:03:26,300 --> 00:03:28,700
I've got one woman too weak to walk.

61
00:03:28,800 --> 00:03:30,200
It's a mathematical problem.

62
00:03:30,400 --> 00:03:32,799
We've got your friends,
plus another 50 who migrated here.

63
00:03:32,800 --> 00:03:34,800
That's too many people,
and not enough food.

64
00:03:34,900 --> 00:03:37,350
We'll just have to figure out
how to make what we have last.

65
00:03:37,400 --> 00:03:38,900
I say the first thing we do,

66
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:40,800
is stop giving it away to strangers.

67
00:04:26,800 --> 00:04:29,500
What if we cut
the food rations in half,

68
00:04:29,800 --> 00:04:30,800
again?

69
00:04:31,149 --> 00:04:32,999
It's more than the food.
What about medicine?

70
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:34,216
Those refugees came here sick.

71
00:04:34,249 --> 00:04:36,299
They've been burning through
our meds for a month.

72
00:04:36,300 --> 00:04:38,100
Can we make it to spring, Harry?

73
00:04:38,700 --> 00:04:40,100
Some of us can. Not all.

74
00:04:41,100 --> 00:04:42,900
Crime's been going up
since they got here.

75
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:44,699
Crime's been going up
since the bombs.

76
00:04:44,700 --> 00:04:47,200
It's got to be done.
The numbers speak for themselves.

77
00:04:47,300 --> 00:04:48,099
Just look at 'em.

78
00:04:48,132 --> 00:04:50,300
I don't need to look at 'em.
I see them in my sleep.

79
00:04:52,200 --> 00:04:53,200
What are you going to do?

80
00:04:56,700 --> 00:04:57,700
Folks?

81
00:04:57,800 --> 00:04:58,800
Folks, listen up!

82
00:04:59,900 --> 00:05:01,699
I am sorry to say that

83
00:05:01,700 --> 00:05:05,000
the town no longer has the resources
to take care of you.

84
00:05:05,400 --> 00:05:07,000
<i>What?
Where are we supposed to go?

85
00:05:07,800 --> 00:05:10,499
So if you could please
gather up your belongings,

86
00:05:10,500 --> 00:05:12,899
you will be escorted
to a FEMA camp out

87
00:05:12,900 --> 00:05:15,400
- near I-70.
- We've been to those FEMA camps.

88
00:05:16,200 --> 00:05:18,000
We barely made it out
alive the first time.

89
00:05:18,600 --> 00:05:22,200
FEMA has medicine and supplies,
and we don't.

90
00:05:22,400 --> 00:05:23,900
You heard the mayor.

91
00:05:24,800 --> 00:05:26,000
You need to start packing up.

92
00:05:26,600 --> 00:05:28,400
What are you going to do,
put us in jail?

93
00:05:28,600 --> 00:05:29,600
Great.

94
00:05:30,300 --> 00:05:31,600
If I didn't have to do this,

95
00:05:32,100 --> 00:05:34,000
- I wouldn't.
- We've been working!

96
00:05:34,300 --> 00:05:36,400
Okay? We've been chopping wood!

97
00:05:36,500 --> 00:05:38,900
Jessica's been helping you
with your medical center.

98
00:05:41,900 --> 00:05:42,900
I'm sorry.

99
00:05:43,100 --> 00:05:44,500
But if you put us out on the...

100
00:05:45,300 --> 00:05:46,600
This isn't a debate.

101
00:05:50,300 --> 00:05:51,300
You're right.

102
00:05:51,700 --> 00:05:52,800
'Cause we're staying.

103
00:06:04,267 --> 00:06:06,366
